{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"22057c03-79b8-4a76-bfad-e8cfbb973ad7","content":"Here's the diagnosis and recommendations:\n\n**Root cause:** Each `dotnet build` invocation spawns a new MSBuild process, loads SDKs, and re-evaluates the project graph. Visual Studio avoids this by keeping a long-running MSBuild node. The project itself is fine — the overhead is process startup, not compilation.\n\n**Fixes (most to least impactful):**\n\n1. **Enable MSBuild Server** — keeps an MSBuild worker process alive between builds, just like VS does:\n   ```bash\n   export DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\n   dotnet build\n   ```\n\n2. **Skip restore on no-op rebuilds** — NuGet restore has overhead even when nothing changed:\n   ```bash\n   dotnet build --no-restore\n   ```\n\n3. **Use `dotnet watch`** for edit-build-test cycles — eliminates process startup entirely by watching for file changes:\n   ```bash\n   dotnet watch run\n   ```\n\n4. **Combine** for maximum effect:\n   ```bash\n   export DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\n   dotnet build --no-restore   # ~sub-second incremental builds\n   ```\n\nThe MSBuild Server (`#1`) is the single biggest win — it's the same mechanism that makes VS fast. You can set the environment variable in your shell profile (`.bashrc`/`.zshrc`) to make it permanent.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9f56774a-aaa3-4902-9ed3-9b6bc90716c6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer reports that `dotnet build` from CLI is slow (2-4 seconds) for incremental builds even when nothing changed, while Visual Studio rebuilds nearly instantly.\n\nThe key insight here is that Visual Studio uses MSBuild Server (a long-running MSBuild process) which avoids the cold-start overhead of re-launching the MSBuild process and re-evaluating the project graph on every build. When you run `dotnet build` from the CLI, each invocation spawns a new MSBuild process, loads all SDKs, evaluates the project, etc.\n\nThe solutions:\n\n1. **Use MSBuild Server (`-graphBuild` with server)**: Starting with .NET 8 / MSBuild 17.9+, there's an MSBuild Server feature. You can enable it by setting the environment variable `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` or using `-p:UseMSBuildServer=true`. This keeps an MSBuild process running between builds, similar to what VS does.\n\n\n2. **Use `dotnet watch`**: For development workflows, `dotnet watch` is a more practical approach that watches for file changes and rebuilds automatically, which is often faster for the inner loop than repeatedly running `dotnet build` manually.\n\n3. **Use `-graph:true`**: For multi-project solutions, MSBuild graph builds can provide better parallelization and efficiency.\n\n4. **Use `--no-restore`**: If dependencies haven't changed, skipping the restore step can save time on subsequent builds.\n\nI should also consider whether there are project-level optimizations...\n\nThe real bottleneck here is MSBuild startup overhead, not the actual compilation since they mentioned it's under 500ms. The main wins are enabling the MSBuild Server to keep the process warm between builds, using `dotnet watch run` to avoid repeated process startup during development, and skipping NuGet restore when packages haven't changed. I'm also thinking about whether disabling documentation file generation would help reduce build time.","outputTokens":1439,"requestId":"7C30:2FFBCA:B32ACD:CB6D84:6A02792D"},"id":"59f07496-8c0a-41d0-9eb8-d9ba41463ec6","timestamp":"2026-05-12T00:50:20.407Z","parentId":"d039e95a-ed13-4f3e-94c9-edfd660a6d46"}
